      <text>Something dropped from the canopy ahead of her.

Kira stopped dead, heart hammering against her ribs. Her hand went instinctively to the emergency beacon at her belt, though what good that would do—

The thing sat on the groundcover, completely still — round, maybe the size of a basketball. The surface looked brownish-green and fuzzy — not fur, but something plant-like, thin branches or leaves woven tight together. It just sat there in the filtered purple light, utterly motionless.

¶

Not threatening — just… there.

Kira stared at it. It stared back. Did it stare? There were no eyes visible, but she felt a «presence» to it, an awareness.

Kira whispered, &quot;Buddy. What am I looking at?&quot;

Suit reported, &quot;Scanning now. I&#39;m detecting plant-based organic material, but the locomotion mechanism is—&quot;

The sphere bounced once, a small hop maybe ten centimeters off the ground.

Kira jumped back, pain flaring in her leg.

The sphere bounced again, rolling slightly forward — toward her.

Kira breathed, &quot;Oh shit.&quot;

The sphere — the «plant ball» — bounced closer, not fast, not aggressive. The movement had a quality like watching a butterfly move: controlled, deliberate. It bounced in a gentle arc, rolled to a stop, then bounced again — not random, not mindless.

Curious — it circled around her at a careful distance, and Kira turned to keep it in view, wincing as her injured leg protested. The plant sphere continued its circuit, observing her from different angles — or at least it felt like observation.

Kira tried, &quot;Hello?&quot;

The sphere kept bouncing — no response, just that same gentle tumbling movement.

Kira asked, &quot;Buddy, is it trying to communicate?&quot;

Suit reported, &quot;I&#39;m not receiving any communication signals on standard frequencies. Perhaps it doesn&#39;t possess—&quot;

The plant ball rolled closer, stopping about a meter away. Close enough that Kira could see the surface wasn&#39;t smooth — tiny branches shifted and repositioned themselves like fingers flexing. The whole thing seemed to breathe, or pulse, or «something».

Living — definitely living, and moving with clear purpose.

Her heart was still racing, but it didn&#39;t feel threatening — more like when you meet a friendly dog and it sniffs you, trying to figure out what you are.

Curious — investigating.

Kira wondered, &quot;Was that a yes? Or just… more bouncing?&quot;

She crouched down slowly, careful of her injured leg. Kira said, &quot;I&#39;m Kira — I crashed here — I don&#39;t know if you can understand me, but I&#39;m not— I&#39;m not trying to hurt anything — I just need water and—&quot;

The sphere rolled forward, closer, right up to her, examining. It began to circle her again, but slower this time — deliberate. It stopped at her injured leg — the bandage visible through her torn pants — and bounced in place, focused.

Kira held very still.</text>
