      <text>A small tendril extended from the sphere&#39;s surface—thin, delicate, reaching toward her bandage, getting closer.

Kira&#39;s breath caught as the tendril came within five centimeters—stretching out so carefully, so _gently_…

She jerked back, scrambling to her feet. Pain exploded through her leg and she gasped, grabbing at the injury.

The plant ball immediately rolled backward—fast, several meters—then stopped. It just sat there, not approaching.

Kira stood, breathing hard, one hand pressed against her thigh; her heart hammered. That had been pure instinct, a pure fear response—something unknown reaching for her and every animal part of her brain screamed _danger_.

But looking at the sphere now… it hadn&#39;t been moving—it had backed off the instant she flinched, given her space.

It hadn&#39;t been attacking. It had been… what? Concerned? Curious about her injury? Trying to help?

Kira said, &quot;I&#39;m sorry. You startled me. I didn&#39;t mean to…&quot;

The plant ball didn&#39;t move—just sat there, waiting.

Buddy said, &quot;Kira, I don&#39;t think it&#39;s hostile. The approach patterns suggest curiosity rather than predatory behavior.&quot;

Kira said, &quot;I know. I know—it&#39;s just…&quot;

First contact—actual alien first contact—and she&#39;d flinched away like it was going to hurt her.

She took a slow breath, then crouched down again. She said, &quot;It&#39;s okay. You can—I&#39;m okay. I just got scared.&quot;

The sphere hesitated—then rolled forward slowly, stopping closer this time but still not touching, giving her space.

They regarded each other.

¶

No words, no shared language, but _something_ passed between them—some kind of… recognition. The plant was curious; Kira was curious—both trying to figure out what the other was.

The moment hung in the purple twilight, in the eerie quiet of the alien forest—human and plant-thing watching each other.

Then the sphere suddenly shifted—its whole surface rippling as branches realigned; it oriented toward the trees. No eyes, but the direction was unmistakable.

Kira heard more movement now—the rustling in the canopy, the sound of many things moving through the branches.

The plant ball bounced once more—a quick little hop that felt like acknowledgment, or farewell, or _something_—then tumbled away rapidly toward the approaching sounds, disappearing into the purple shadows between the trees.

Kira stood slowly, breathing hard. That had been first contact—an actual alien life form, a bouncing plant ball that couldn&#39;t speak. And somehow, for a moment, they&#39;d understood each other.

The sounds were getting closer—more rustling, more movement; more of them coming.

Kira straightened, heart pounding again for entirely different reasons.

Time to find out what else lived on this planet.</text>
